50|$|Trammel v. United States, 445 U.S. 40 (1980), is a United States Supreme Court case {{involving}} the <b>spousal</b> <b>privilege</b> and its application {{in the law}} of evidence. In it, the Court held that the witness-spouse alone has a privilege to refuse to testify adversely; the witness may be neither compelled to testify nor foreclosed from testifying.|$|E
